The concurrency aspects were also thoroughly examined. The `kernel_param_lock` serializes concurrent accesses to the module parameters, so this prevents race conditions during sysfs writes. The use of a per-module lock ensures safe concurrent access. I reviewed that `damon_call` uses a completion and blocks, so stack allocated struct `control`'s stack memory is perfectly safe.

The analysis revealed that the kdamond now applies parameters during `damon_call`, by calling the `commit_inputs_fn` function, which, in turn, calls `damon_lru_sort_apply_parameters()` and `damon_reclaim_apply_parameters()`. This allows a simplified design, since `commit_inputs` is no longer a periodic check. This also removes a code path in the slow path that previously called `handle_commit_inputs()` from `kdamond` thread.

